AxB is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) where a is an element of A and b is an element of B. Similarly, BxA is the set of all ordered pairs (b, a) where b is an element of B and a is an element of A.

AxB = {(1, 2), (1, 3), (2, 2), (2, 3)}
BxA = {(2, 1), (3, 1), (2, 2), (3, 2)}

Now let's find AxB ∩ BxA and BxA ∩ AxB.

AxB ∩ BxA is the set of all ordered pairs that are in both AxB and BxA.
AxB ∩ BxA = {(2, 2)}

BxA ∩ AxB is the set of all ordered pairs that are in both BxA and AxB.
BxA ∩ AxB = {(2, 2)}

Since AxB ∩ BxA = BxA ∩ AxB, the statement is true.
